Spatial autocorrelation OU Version 2

The simulations described here are part of a series documenting the effect of breaching assumptions of spatially explicit capturerecapture models.

Problem description

SECR assumes successive detections of an individual are independent events, conditional on the location of the activity centre. The Ornstein-Uhlenbeck distribution provides a serially correlated model of animal movement that may be used to test the effect of non-independence on SECR estimates.

Settings

Square grid of 64 count proximity detectors at spacing 100 m.

The same conditions were used for simulation and fitting.

Parameter Value(s)
detectfn HHN
D 2 / ha
lambda0 NA
sigma 100
tau 0.1, 1, 5, 10, 20, 50, 100
epsilon 10 m
noccasions 100
buffer 500 m
nx 32
nrepl 200

Here sigma is the overall scale of the O-U distribution and tau determines the serial correlation. An animal is considered to be detected when it is within epsilon of a detector at one of noccasions sampling occasions.

Simulation code

From secr 5.2.5 it is possible to simulate OU movement and detection directly in secr. Detection happens when the location of an animal at one time step is within epsilon of a detector. The output capthist is a single-occasion sample.

grid   <- make.grid(nx = 8, ny = 8, spacing = 100, detector = "count")
msk    <- make.mask(grid, buffer = 500, type = 'trapbuffer')
nstep  <- 100
fitarg <- list(detectfn = 'HHN', binomN = 1)
taulevels <- c(0.1, 1, 5, 10, 20, 50, 100)
scen <- make.scenarios( D = 2, epsilon = 10, sigma = 100, tau = taulevels,
                        noccasions = nstep, detectfn = 20)
OUsims <- run.scenarios(
    nrepl       = nrepl, 
    scenarios   = scen, 
    trapset     = grid, 
    maskset     = msk,
    fit         = TRUE, 
    fit.args    = fitarg, 
    seed        = 12345)
saveRDS(OUsims, file = 'OUsims.RDS')

OUsims completed with 200 replicates in 100 minutes.

Results

First display some examples of movement tracks.

par(mfrow=c(2,2), mar = c(1,1,2,1), pty='s')
set.seed(123)
for (tau in c(0.1,1,10,100)) {
    locs <- simOU(matrix(c(0,0), nrow=1), tau = tau, sigma = 100, noccasions = 100)
    plot (locs, type='o', xlim=c(-350,350), ylim = c(-350,350), axes=F, xlab='', ylab='')
    mtext(side = 3, paste('tau = ', tau))
    points(0,0, pch = 16, col='red', cex = 1.2)
    box()
    symbols(0,0,circles=245,inches=FALSE, add = TRUE, fg = grey(0.8))
}

Figure: Examples of correlated movement paths over 100 time steps. Red dot is activity centre; grey circle is 95% contour of activity.

Interpretation

In these simulations autocorrelation was damaging (\(|\mbox{RB}(\hat D)| > 0.05\) only when \(\tau \ge 50\). This suggests that autocorrelation per se is not a problem; it is possible some other effect comes into play for large \(\tau\).

One-off

Run this code to obtain results for a single scenario.

source('../setup.R')
grid   <- make.grid(nx = 8, ny = 8, spacing = 100, detector = "count")
msk    <- make.mask(grid, buffer = 500, type = 'trapbuffer')
fitarg <- list(binomN = 1, detectfn = 'HHN')
scen   <- make.scenarios( D = 2, epsilon = 10, sigma = 100, tau = 100, 
                        noccasions = 100, detectfn = 20)
oneoff <- run.scenarios(nrepl = 10, scen, trapset = grid,  maskset = msk,
    fit = TRUE, fit.args = fitarg, seed = 12345)
